{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492634","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492634"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:38:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:38:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1116"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1116"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.02,0.2,0.02,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1116"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69134"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1116"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1116"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54591"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"266"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1126"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9134"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"737"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44499"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69134"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-year history of intermittent rectal bleeding. He describes the painless passage of a small amount of fresh blood whenever he passes a constipated stool. He has not tried anything to relieve constipation in the past. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He works as an office manager and eats a well-balanced diet with regular intake of fruit and vegetables.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The only abnormality detected are internal haemorrhoids, visible just beyond the anal verge when he strains. Digital rectal examination and proctosigmoidoscopy are otherwise normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase fluid intake and stool softeners","Haemorrhoidal artery ligation","Rubber band ligation","Sclerotherapy","Haemorrhoidectomy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with Grade II haemorrhoids, characterised by protrusion beyond the anal verge with straining and spontaneous reduction. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemorrhoids can be classified into the following Grades:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI: protrusion into the anal canal, occasional bleeding, but no prolapse\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EII: protrusion beyond the anal verge with straining or defaecation and spontaneous reduction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIII: spontaneous protrusion or as the result of straining, requiring manual reduction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIV: permanent prolapse and unable to be reduced\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe first-line treatment for Grade I-II haemorrhoids is conservative management. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncrease fluid intake and stool softeners\u003C/strong\u003E, along with dietary modification to increase fibre intake, can effectively manage symptoms in most cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemorrhoidal artery ligation\u003C/strong\u003E is a minimally invasive surgical technique that reduces blood flow to haemorrhoids. While effective, it is typically reserved for patients who have failed conservative management or have more severe disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERubber band ligation\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered for Grade II haemorrhoids that fail conservative management. However, it would be inappropriate to proceed directly to this intervention before trying conservative measures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESclerotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E involves injection of sclerosing agents into haemorrhoids. While it can be used for Grade I-II haemorrhoids, it has largely been superseded by other treatments and should not be first-line therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemorrhoidectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for Grade IV haemorrhoids or Grade III cases with severe symptoms. It would be excessive for this patient\u0027s Grade II disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Grade I-II haemorrhoids should be managed initially with conservative measures including increased dietary fibre and fluid intake.","Surgical interventions for haemorrhoids should be reserved for cases that fail conservative management or higher grades of disease.","The grade of haemorrhoids (I-IV) determines the most appropriate management strategy."],"references":["Muldoon R. Review of American Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Hemorrhoids. JAMA Surg. 2020;155(8):773-774. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32584937/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54591"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1116"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54591"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T10:43:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T10:43:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"